'''Cameron Robert Burgess''' (born 21 October 1995) is a professional [[Association football|soccer]] player who plays as a [[Defender (association football)#Centre-back|centre-back]] for {{English football updater|SwanseaC}} club [[Swansea City A.F.C.|Swansea City]]. Born in Scotland, he represents the [[Australia men's national soccer team|Australia national team]].

==Early life==
Originally from Portlethen in Aberdeenshire. Burgess's grandfather is Scottish retired international footballer [[Campbell Forsyth]].<ref name="International switch" /> His father, [[Stuart Burgess]], was also a professional player. His family emigrated from Scotland to [[Perth]], Australia when he was 11 years old.<ref name="International switch" />

==Club career==
===Fulham and loans===
Burgess joined the Fulham Academy in 2011 from [[ECU Joondalup SC|ECU Joondalup]] and signed a professional contract with the club in July 2013.<ref name="profile"/> He made his [[first team (association football)|first team]] debut for Fulham, in a 2–1 away loss in the opening match of the 2014–15 [[The Football League Championship|Championship]] season on 9 August 2014 against [[Ipswich Town F.C.|Ipswich Town]] at [[Portman Road]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/28646535|title=Ipswich Town 2–1 Fulham|work=BBC Sport|date=9 August 2014|access-date=13 August 2014|archive-date=19 December 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141219122705/http://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/28646535|url-status=live}}</ref>

On 15 January 2015, Burgess signed a contract extension with Fulham until June 2017, with an option for another year, and on the same day signed on loan for [[Scottish Premiership]] club [[Ross County F.C.|Ross County]] until the end of the 2014–15 season.<ref>{{cite web|title=Extension & loan for Burgess|url=http://www.fulhamfc.com/news/2015/january/15/burgess-new-deal|publisher=[[Fulham F.C.|Fulham]]|date=15 January 2015|access-date=15 January 2015|archive-date=15 January 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150115203205/http://www.fulhamfc.com/news/2015/january/15/burgess-new-deal|url-status=live}}</ref>

Burgess joined [[Cheltenham Town F.C.|Cheltenham Town]] of the [[National League (division)|National League]] on loan on 26 January 2016 for the remainder of the 2015–16 season.<ref>{{cite web|title=Burgess' Cheltenham Loan|url=http://www.fulhamfc.com/news/2016/january/26/burgess-cheltenham-loan|publisher=[[Fulham F.C.|Fulhan]]|date=26 January 2016|access-date=26 January 2016|archive-date=1 February 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160201164918/http://www.fulhamfc.com/news/2016/january/26/burgess-cheltenham-loan|url-status=live}}</ref>

On 18 July 2016, Burgess joined [[Football League One|League One]] club [[Oldham Athletic A.F.C.|Oldham Athletic]] on a six-month loan deal.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fulhamfc.com/news/2016/july/18/burgess-oldham-loan|title=Burgess' Oldham Loan|publisher=[[Fulham F.C.|Fulham]]|date=18 July 2016|access-date=18 July 2016|archive-date=21 July 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160721075915/http://www.fulhamfc.com/news/2016/july/18/burgess-oldham-loan|url-status=live}}</ref> He made his debut on 6 August 2016 in a 3–0 loss to [[Millwall F.C.|Millwall]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.newsatden.co.uk/57662-live-millwall-vs-oldham-athletic.html|title=Report: Millwall 3–0 Oldham Athletic|first=John|last=Kelly|publisher=News at Den|date=6 August 2016|access-date=14 August 2016|archive-date=19 August 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160819015051/http://www.newsatden.co.uk/57662-live-millwall-vs-oldham-athletic.html|url-status=live}}</ref> He scored his first goal for Oldham in a 1–1 draw with [[Oxford United]] on 10 December 2016.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/38192532|title=Oxford 1–1 Oldham|publisher=BBC|date=10 December 2016|access-date=19 December 2016|archive-date=14 December 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161214184651/http://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/38192532|url-status=live}}</ref>

On 6 January 2017, he moved to [[Bury F.C.|Bury]] on loan for six months.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/38534798|title=Bury: Taylor Moore, Reece Brown and Cameron Burgess join League One club|work=[[BBC Sport]]|date=6 January 2017|access-date=12 February 2018|archive-date=1 February 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170201041547/http://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/38534798|url-status=live}}</ref>

===Scunthorpe United===
On 6 June 2017, Burgess joined [[Scunthorpe United F.C.|Scunthorpe United]] on a three-year contract.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/40176154|title=Cameron Burgess: Scunthorpe sign Fulham central defender on a three-year contract|work=[[BBC Sport]]|date=6 June 2017|access-date=12 February 2018|archive-date=25 October 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221025132849/https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/40176154|url-status=live}}</ref> He scored his first goal for the club in a 0–3 away win over [[Northampton Town F.C.|Northampton Town]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/41951499|title=Northampton Town 0–3 Scunthorpe United|work=[[BBC Sport]]|date=18 November 2017|access-date=12 February 2018|archive-date=29 December 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171229004125/http://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/41951499|url-status=live}}</ref>

On 24 July 2019 he joined [[Salford City F.C.|Salford City]] on a season-long loan.<ref>{{cite web |title=Cameron Burgess signs on loan |url=https://salfordcityfc.co.uk/cameron-burgess-signs-on-loan/ |publisher=Salford City F.C. |access-date=22 February 2020 |archive-date=11 October 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191011191146/https://salfordcityfc.co.uk/cameron-burgess-signs-on-loan/ |url-status=live }}</ref>

===Accrington Stanley===
On 3 August 2020 he joined [[Accrington Stanley F.C.|Accrington Stanley]] on a 3-year deal.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.accringtonstanley.co.uk/news/2020/august/burgess-first-summer-signing/|title=Burgess first summer signing|website=www.accringtonstanley.co.uk|access-date=3 August 2020|archive-date=20 September 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200920084010/https://www.accringtonstanley.co.uk/news/2020/august/burgess-first-summer-signing/|url-status=live}}</ref> He scored on his debut for Accrington in an [[EFL Cup]] tie against [[Burton Albion]].<ref>{{Cite web|title=Burgess first summer signing|url=https://www.accringtonstanley.co.uk/news/2020/august/burgess-first-summer-signing/|access-date=27 July 2021|website=www.accringtonstanley.co.uk|language=en-gb|archive-date=5 August 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210805121126/https://www.accringtonstanley.co.uk/news/2020/august/burgess-first-summer-signing/|url-status=live}}</ref> He also scored on his second appearance in an [[EFL Trophy]] tie against [[Leeds United F.C. Reserves and Youth Team|Leeds United U21s]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://throughitalltogether.sbnation.com/2020/9/8/21427573/match-recap-and-ratings-accrington-stanley-7-0-leeds-united-u21s |title=Match Recap and Ratings: Accrington Stanley 7 – 0 Leeds United u21s |publisher=throughitalltogether.com |date=8 September 2020 |access-date=9 September 2020 |archive-date=10 September 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200910151255/https://throughitalltogether.sbnation.com/2020/9/8/21427573/match-recap-and-ratings-accrington-stanley-7-0-leeds-united-u21s |url-status=live }}</ref>

===Ipswich Town===
On 15 August 2021, Burgess joined [[EFL League One]] club [[Ipswich Town F.C.|Ipswich Town]] on a three-year contract for an undisclosed fee, with the contract having the option for an additional one-year extension.<ref>{{Cite web | url = https://www.itfc.co.uk/news/2021/august/town-complete-cameron-burgess-signing/ | publisher = [[Ipswich Town F.C.]] | title = Burgess is a Blue | access-date = 15 August 2021 | date = 15 August 2021 | archive-date = 15 August 2021 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20210815140208/https://www.itfc.co.uk/news/2021/august/town-complete-cameron-burgess-signing/ | url-status = live }}</ref> He made his debut for Ipswich two days later in a 1–2 away loss against former loan club Cheltenham Town.<ref>{{Cite web | url = https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/58154371 | publisher = [[BBC Sport]] | title = Cheltenham Town 2 - 1 Ipswich Town | access-date = 8 November 2021 | date = 17 August 2021 | archive-date = 8 November 2021 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20211108145615/https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/58154371 | url-status = live }}</ref>

The draw with Watford was Burgess' 101st appearance for the Blues after the East Anglian derby at Carrow Road earned him a spot in the club's 100 club.On his achievement, he said: "It's a privilege to be able to play 100 games for this football club, infront of these fans. Everytime you get the chance to play at Portman Road it's a special occasion."<ref>{{Cite web |date=2024-04-10 |title='Things are in our hands' – Burgess remains positive after Watford stalemate |url=https://www.suffolknews.co.uk/ipswich/sport/things-are-in-our-hands-burgess-remains-positive-after-w-9361102/ |access-date=2024-04-12 |website=Suffolk News |language=en}}</ref>

On 3 June 2024, Ipswich said they had extended the player's contract by a year.<ref>{{Cite web |date=2024-06-03 |title=RETAINED LIST CONFIRMED |url=https://www.itfc.co.uk/news/2024/june/03/ipswich-town-retained-list-summer-2024/ |access-date=2024-06-06 |website=www.itfc.co.uk |language=en}}</ref>

===Swansea City===
On 14 June 2025, Burgess agreed to join Championship side [[Swansea City A.F.C.|Swansea City]] on a three-year contract.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.swanseacity.com/news/cameron-burgess-seals-swansea-city-move|title=Cameron Burgess seals Swansea City move|website=www.swanseacity.com|language=en|access-date=14 June 2025|date=14 June 2025|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20250615161130/https://www.swanseacity.com/news/cameron-burgess-seals-swansea-city-move|archive-date=15 June 2025|url-status=live}}</ref> Upon joining the club, he was given a number fifteen shirt.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.swanseacity.com/news/swansea-city-confirm-2025-26-mens-squad-numbers|title=Swansea City confirm 2025-26 men's squad numbers|website=www.swanseacity.com|language=en|date=7 August 2025|access-date=18 September 2025|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20250918064158/https://www.swanseacity.com/news/swansea-city-confirm-2025-26-mens-squad-numbers|archive-date=18 September 2025|url-status=live}}</ref>

Burgess made his Swansea City's debut, starting the whole game, in a 1–0 loss against [[Middlesbrough F.C.|Middlesbrough]] in the opening game of the season.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.swanseacity.com/news/report-middlesbrough-1-swansea-city-0-1|title=Report: Middlesbrough 1 Swansea City 0|website=www.swanseacity.com|language=en|date=9 August 2025|access-date=18 September 2025|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20250918064535/https://www.swanseacity.com/news/report-middlesbrough-1-swansea-city-0-1|archive-date=18 September 2025|url-status=live}}</ref> In a follow-up match, he captained for the club for the first time against [[Crawley Town F.C.|Crawley Town]] in the first round of the League Cup and  led to a 3–1 win.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.swanseacity.com/news/report-swansea-city-3-crawley-town-1|title=Report: Swansea City 3 Crawley Town 1|website=www.swanseacity.com|language=en|date=12 August 2025|access-date=18 September 2025|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20250918064724/https://www.swanseacity.com/news/report-swansea-city-3-crawley-town-1|archive-date=18 September 2025|url-status=live}}</ref> 

On 17 September 2025, Burgess scored twice in Swansea City’s 3–2 victory over [[Nottingham Forest F.C.|Nottingham Forest]] in the Carabao Cup third round. He began the comeback with Swansea’s first goal and later secured the win with a stoppage-time strike, sending the club into the last 16.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.swanseacity.com/news/report-swansea-city-3-nottingham-forest-2|title=Report: Swansea City 3 Nottingham Forest 2|website=www.swanseacity.com|language=en|date=17 September 2025|access-date=18 September 2025|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20250918064904/https://www.swanseacity.com/news/report-swansea-city-3-nottingham-forest-2|archive-date=18 September 2025|url-status=live}}</ref> On 8 November 2025, Burgess scored two own goals in a 4–1 home loss against his former club Ipswich Town. He later apologised to Swansea fans on social media for his part in the team's poor performance.<ref>{{Cite web |date=2025-11-09 |title=Swansea City news: Cameron Burgess sends 'no excuses' message after Ipswich loss |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/articles/cy5q2l3l4lro |access-date=2025-11-09 |website=BBC Sport |language=en-GB}}</ref>

==International career==
===Scotland===
Burgess played for Scotland at [[Scotland national under-18 football team|under-18]] and [[Scotland national under-19 football team|under-19]] levels and took part in the [[2014 UEFA European Under-19 Championship qualification]] campaign, playing the full game against Latvia in a 1–1 draw.<ref>{{cite web|title=Under-19 2014 – Scotland-Latvia – UEFA.com|url=https://www.uefa.com/under19/match/2011110--scotland-vs-latvia/|publisher=[[UEFA]]|access-date=3 October 2014|date=10 October 2013|archive-date=7 October 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141007033201/http://www.uefa.com/under19/season=2014/matches/round=2000383/match=2011110/postmatch/commentary/index.html|url-status=live}}</ref>

===Australia===
In September 2014 Burgess switched his allegiance permanently to Australia.<ref name="International switch">{{cite web|title=Australia wins battle with Scotland for promising football star Cameron Burgess|url=http://www.perthnow.com.au/sport/football/australia-wins-battle-with-scotland-for-promising-football-star-cameron-burgess/story-fnhq5z8s-1227050386264?nk=daeb6a30feec0b351f819a288028b1f2|date=7 September 2014|access-date=7 September 2014|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140907234051/http://www.perthnow.com.au/sport/football/australia-wins-battle-with-scotland-for-promising-football-star-cameron-burgess/story-fnhq5z8s-1227050386264?nk=daeb6a30feec0b351f819a288028b1f2|archive-date=7 September 2014}}</ref> He was named in the Australia squad for the [[2014 AFC U-19 Championship]] held in [[Myanmar]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Okon optimistic as Young Socceroos target World Cup|url=http://www.the-afc.com/en/tournaments/men/afc-u19-championship/29547-okon-optimistic-as-young-socceroos-target-world-cup.html|publisher=The-AFC.com|access-date=3 October 2014|date=30 September 2014|archive-date=5 October 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141005190902/http://www.the-afc.com/en/tournaments/men/afc-u19-championship/29547-okon-optimistic-as-young-socceroos-target-world-cup.html|url-status=live}}</ref>

16 March 2015, Burgess was selected as one of twelve overseas based players in a squad of twenty three by head-coach, [[Aurelio Vidmar]], to take part in the Australian Olyroos' qualification campaign on the road to [[2016 Summer Olympics|Brazil 2016 Olympic Games]]. The first stage of qualification began in a tournament held in [[Kaohsiung|Kaohsiung City, Taiwan]], against minnows Hong Kong, Myanmar and hosts Taiwan.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.abc.net.au/news/2015-03-16/road-to-rio-begins-as-olyroos-squad-named/6322700 | title = Olyroos squad of 23 named by Aurelio Vidmar as quest for 2016 Olympic Games qualification begins | work = [[ABC News (Australia)|ABC News]] | date = 16 March 2015 | access-date = 8 January 2016 | archive-date = 7 December 2015 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20151207024837/http://www.abc.net.au/news/2015-03-16/road-to-rio-begins-as-olyroos-squad-named/6322700 | url-status = live }}</ref> The Olyroos progressed past this qualification tournament to qualify for the [[AFC U-23 Championship]], which doubles as the final qualification round for the AFC for the Olympics. On 23 December 2015, Burgess was again selected by Vidmar to form part of the Olyroos squad for the [[2016 AFC U-23 Championship]] held in [[Doha, Qatar]] between 14 and 30 January 2016.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.goal.com/en-au/news/7080/young-socceroos-olyroos/2015/12/23/18632512/socceroos-promotion-a-carrot-for-olyroos-vidmar | title=Socceroos promotion a carrot for Olyroos – Vidmar | publisher=[[Perform Group|Goal.com]] | first=John | last=Greco | date=23 December 2015 | access-date=8 January 2016 | archive-date=6 March 2016 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160306134334/http://www.goal.com/en-au/news/7080/young-socceroos-olyroos/2015/12/23/18632512/socceroos-promotion-a-carrot-for-olyroos-vidmar | url-status=live }}</ref>

Burgess was first selected for the full [[Australia men's national soccer team|Australia]] squad in September 2023.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2023/sep/01/socceroos-australia-vs-mexico-friendly-squad |title=Graham Arnold adds new faces to Socceroos squad for Mexico friendly |newspaper=The Guardian |date=1 September 2023 |accessdate=1 September 2023 |first=Mike |last=Hytner |archive-date=1 September 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230901101711/https://www.theguardian.com/football/2023/sep/01/socceroos-australia-vs-mexico-friendly-squad |url-status=live }}</ref> His debut came in a friendly against [[Mexico national football team|Mexico]] where he played a full game as centre-back, giving away a penalty-kick in the second-half of a 2–2 draw at [[Arlington, Texas]].<ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.socceroos.com.au/match/mexico-v-australia-friendlies-10-09-2023/22278548 |title= Socceroos play out hard-fought Mexico draw |website= Socceroos.com.au |date= 9 September 2023 |access-date= 10 September 2023 |archive-date= 30 July 2023 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20230730110140/https://www.socceroos.com.au/match/mexico-v-australia-friendlies-10-09-2023/22278548 |url-status= live }}</ref>

